history.content: Not sure about your enrollment situation, but the format of the class is similar to CS 70, except that you also have lab (which usually can be done during the allotted time). CS 70 is a lot more theoretical, whereas EE 16A is basically Linear Algebra and its applications + a primer on circuits. If you have taken Math 54 and/or 110, the linear algebra portion will be review, and you will realize that they teach linear algebra mainly in the context of its applications. The circuits portion is not too bad if you have taken Physics 7B. Otherwise, a lot of people found this portion (especially circuit design) to be difficult. The curve for EE 16A is more generous than CS 70 (speaking from personal experience only).

history.content:
Unfortunately, the only way to change secondary sections is to drop yourself from the waitlist and then re-add the class. At # <10 on the waitlist, it is possible that enough people will drop from your lab and you will be enrolled, but we can't know that this will happen for sure.
If you drop and re-add the class, you will be placed at the end of the waitlist. Right now there are 201 students waitlisted. In general, ~10% of students will drop a class by the 5th week of the semester. In 16A's case, that is about 75 students. Being position #200 on the waitlist puts you in an OK position. Again, we unfortunately cannot make any guarantees.
